dogs.name: Relish
dogs.description:
Relish is a sweet, sensitive boy with a big heart who's still learning that the world isn’t such a scary place.  Unfamiliar people and loud noises make him nervous—but don’t let that fool you. Beneath that cautious exterior is a playful, loving, affectionate dog just waiting to shine.
He’s making steady progress in building his confidence every day and just needs someone willing to let him go at his own pace.. What helps most? Other dogs! Relish adores canine companions and really comes alive when around doggie friends. He gains so much comfort and courage from having a friendly dog by his side. He also lights up during a game of fetch—it’s his favorite way to bond and burn off energy.
Relish would do best in a calm, patient home with people who understand that trust takes time.
If you’re the kind of person who believes in giving shy dogs a chance to blossom, Relish is ready to reward your patience with a lifetime of love and loyalty.

﻿Relish is approximately 1y 2m 9d old and is fully grown at 44 pounds. They are microchipped and up to date on all age-appropriate medical care. Their breed is unknown as we have not had a DNA test done.

Although our dogs are listed as unknown breed, buildings with specific dog restrictions typically enforce their rules based on what breeds a dog appears to resemble. It's always important to keep that in mind and know your building's policies before adopting a dog.

This dog is available for adoption through Muddy Paws Rescue. If you're interested in adopting, the first thing you should do is begin the registration process at www.muddypawsrescue.org. If you are already a registered adopter with Muddy Paws Rescue, please email us at adoptionmeetings@muddypawsrescue.org.

dogs.general_personality: Relish is quite a loving boy, sweet and kind. He loves his toys and will take them one by one to play with until he is surrounded by toys on the couch. He esp loves playing fetch with his favorite ball. He really likes making doggy friends and this has helped him greatly in meeting new people.  He loves being with his people getting massages and belly rubs, and playing.
dogs.daily_routine:
6am-Play fetch for about 30-45min, or play with a dog friend
Breakfast upon return
He will usually play with his toys or throw the ball around indoors for 30min-1 hour after breakfast 
8am-11am- will nap at my feet while I work or on his bed
11am: potty break
Training session around 12noon with cheese rewards
1-4pm- nap /play with toys
4pm: potty break
4:30-5pm: Dinner
5-7pm: play with toys/ indoor fetch/ training session
7pm: Potty break
7-9pm: rest or mild play, chews bone
last potty break before bed around 9pm
dogs.leash_behaviors: Does best when its less busy outside.  If its too busy, he will just do his business and want to go back inside. He will pull if he needs to avoid an unfamiliar person or a loud noise catches him off guard. He does have a thing for squirrels and will try to chase them.
dogs.crate_rating_when_alone: 3 - Appears to be crate trained
dogs.other_quirks: He loves a long stretch and will hold a downward dog for a long time, enjoys a gentle massage while in downward dog. Sometimes he likes to hold hands.
dogs.what_makes_him_her_happy: Dogs, toys/ fetch, treats, stretching/ yoga, gentle massages/pets, play wrestling (once he is comfortable with you)
dogs.what_makes_him_her_nervous: Strangers, dogs barking at him, loud noises, combs/brushes
dogs.other_displayed_behaviors: resource guarding towards dogs with ball/ toys/ high value treats.  If the dog lets him get the ball or backs down, then is fine playing alongside the dog. Does not resource guard toward people.
dogs.acclimated_to_environment:
Still getting used to seeing so many strangers in the city and noises, but has been slowly improving. 
He does best outside when its quiet (early mornings or late night) and really looks forward to his early morning play session.
dogs.currently_eating:
Farmers dog (beef, turkey, chicken)-1 pack per day. 
Can be a picky eater and will supplement with Freshpet, Kismet, or make him boiled chicken or ground beef/ turkey and mashed potatoes

dogs.description:
Pippin is blossoming is his new foster home, where he's in a quiet neighborhood outside of the bustling city! He loves to play with his toys and often comes to his foster mom to play with him.  He loves to play outside as well and is pretty good on a leash. He is housebroken, standing by the door when he wants to go out and is trustworthy in the house. He is slow to warm up to new people but with gentle coaxing and treats he is calm although a little standoffish. He loves belly rubs and cuddles. He has a strong prey drive, wanting to run after the squirrels in the neighborhood.  He’s fun to be with and happy when his foster mom comes home. He does well at being alone and we have left him for 8 hours!

﻿Pippin is approximately 1y 9m 19d old and is fully grown at 39 pounds. They are microchipped and up to date on all age-appropriate medical care. Their breed is unknown as we have not had a DNA test done.

dogs.acclimated_to_environment: Pippin is definitely adapting well to a quiet home and neighborhood. He’s trustworthy at home and sleeps in his crate. More and more, Pippin is getting used to loud noises with no need to go home!

Bam has become a bit more leash reactive to dogs over time as he's settled in.

I would love a new family who is extra patient and willing to work with me as I build up my confidence around people. I have a lot of love to give, I'm just figuring out how to do it!

dogs.name: Sugar
dogs.description:
Meet Sugar – a sweet soul with a spunky spirit and a heart full of love

Don’t let my name fool you- I’m more than just sweet. I’m spunky, curious, and full of personality. At 8 years young, I still have plenty of pep in my step for walks, outdoor exploring, and playtime with my favorite humans.

I was born deaf, so I experience the world a little differently, but that doesn’t slow me down one bit. I’m learning sign language (how cool is that?!) and doing great with it, though my foster mom is also teaching me touch signals. What helps me thrive is a calm, structured home with a predictable routine and people who understand that I feel safest when things are steady.

I can get a bit anxious when there’s too much change, but once I know what to expect, I settle right in and show my loving, loyal side. I adore being close to my people- whether it’s curling up on the couch, joining a little adventure, or simply being your shadow.

I’m currently being fostered with both dogs and cats, and I get along beautifully with everyone. I’ve also been around kids and am gentle and patient with them- especially when they offer belly rubs or treats!

And here’s a fun fact: after eight years apart, I was reunited with my birth sister in foster care!

I may not hear when you call me a good girl, but I feel it in my heart every time you show me love. If you’re looking for a gentle, affectionate companion who thrives on routine and will be your loyal best friend through it all, I think we might be the perfect match.

﻿Sugar is approximately 8y 2m 14d old and is fully grown at 35 pounds. They are microchipped and up to date on all age-appropriate medical care. Their breed is unknown as we have not had a DNA test done.

dogs.general_personality: Affogato is quite the outgoing pup! He warmed up to us right away and immediately started trying to sit in our laps. He can definitely get the zoomies and has so much love and energy he sometimes doesn’t know where to put it, but with some structure (and a lot of enrichment) he will be a loyal companion
dogs.daily_routine:
His first walk is usually around 7:30/8 followed by vigorous tug/fetch/flirt pole and scavenger hunt breakfast. We’ve also been giving him 100mg of trazodone first thing in the morning to help ease his energy spikes.

He’ll usually nap after breakfast until around 12/1, when we’ll go for another walk + play + give another 100mg trazodone. When we get back, we’ll usually give him a frozen pb kong or lick mat (his favorite!). 

From 1/2-5/6 he’s usually happy to hang out and chew a bone, maybe will ask for pets and play or he’ll nap. 

At 5/6, we go on another walk and give him 300mg of gabapentin (the nighttime tends to be his witching hours). When we get back, we do dinner the same way as breakfast.

After dinner its helpful to have chews out for him, take away any exciting toys, and expect some zoomies.

We go on a final potty break around 9/10
dogs.leash_behaviors:
He’s actually great on the leash! He’s a big guy and can pull when he’s excited/overstimulated in crowded areas but he’s very treat motivated and is responsive outside. He has a tendency to try to eat food off the ground though so have to watch for that!

He seems interested in other dogs but doesn’t otherwise react to them. He is also very interested in squirrels. He also gets a bit spooked by motorcycles/skateboards on the sidewalk.
dogs.crate_rating_when_alone: 1 - Appears to need significant work on crate training (exhibits extreme signs of stress for over an hour)

When we’ve tried to leave him completely alone he has rammed himself into his crate so we’re working up to it. He has been prescribed trazodone and gabapentin so we’re working on figuring out the right combination of dosage and training to get him comfortable!

dogs.general_personality:
I'd sum up Luke as skittish. He's not necessarily shy though. A neighbor dog stopped by and Luke happily ran up to him to say hi with proper manners and did not push the dog at all. 

He hangs out with my husband in the evenings as part of our regular nightly routine with our toddler and my husband informed me Luke got startled by his own reflection in our front door. He's working on confronting his reflections throughout the house lol
dogs.daily_routine:
7:30/8A Morning walk
8:30A Breakfast (shows ZERO food aggression. Even lets the cat nibble)
10:30-4P We walk Luke roughly every 2.5-3 hours for reliving himself. But admittedly go out more frequently for playtime as well. 
5:30/6P Dinner
**My husband stays downstairs to clean so he'll walk Luke a few times and as close to 'last call' as possible. Last walk of the evening is usually close to 10P**
dogs.leash_behaviors: Luke has mostly been let out on a 30 ft lead and he has adjusted amazingly. He very quickly learned to feel out what the limit of the leash is and if he yanks it’s mostly by accident. We’re working on polite walking on the short leash and he’s improved so much! It helps immensely for him to be with my older dog who remains calm.
dogs.crate_rating_when_alone: 3 - Appears to be crate trained
dogs.other_quirks: N/A
dogs.what_makes_him_her_happy: Luke LOVES the company of his foster sister. Brie is ~10 y/o so has shown Luke the ropes. Zoomies, tug of war, fetch all happen with Brie.
dogs.what_makes_him_her_nervous:
Loud noises, sudden movements (like my toddler running around), fast approaches (even if it's myself or my husband coming down the stairs), anything new (he got startled by one of my chickens just moving lol). 

We had one guest overnight (my mom) for Thanksgiving. We prepared everyone for the meet and greet and it went so well. 

We let Luke observe from behind the gate in his “room” (not the crate). He got to see how my dogs recognized and reacted to my guest. When he calmed down a bit we leashed him and actually ignored the guest to just walk around the kitchen, get some treats and bring down the energy a few notches. Then the introduction was very short and sweet. Guest stayed still, slowly put hand out for her to sniff, and then Luke walked away. The new presence sometimes startled Luke, like in the morning when someone totally new came down the stairs but he handled it very well.
dogs.other_displayed_behaviors: Luke showed a lot of anxiety when one of my guests approached a bit strong and surprised him. Luckily it was behind a gate upstairs and the situation was diffused immediately. He seemed a bit nervous with me when we went into a quiet room, but that was also quickly remedied with lots of reassuring words and cuddles. After a few solid minutes of decompression time, Luke was feeling much better and we went downstairs to his crate.
dogs.acclimated_to_environment: He is doing GREAT. There are a few unique factors at play though: the whole family is home 24/7, we're in a rural area so it's very quiet (the loudest noise he encountered outside was a neighbor's rooster), and I have him on a 30 ft lead a few times a day to work on training like recall but also letting him explore.
dogs.currently_eating: We give our dogs kirkland kibble and supplement with homecooked meals like bone broth soup, vegetables, etc. We just make extra portions of whatever we're eating that's dog-safe.

dogs.name: Coconut
dogs.description:
Coconut is just an absolute gem. Lovable, cuddly, and sweet—everyone she meets immediately loves her and people will stop me on the street just to say hi. She loves long walks and exploring her neighborhood (sometimes hard to get her to come back inside, but once she’s in she’s turns into a complete couch potato!). Big fan of belly rubs, a nice long bone to chew for hours or a toy to chase around. She behaves very well on walks, with some light pulling which has improved a ton with her new double leash. She also generally does not get distracted by other dogs or noises on walks (but always on the lookout for squirrels!). A good listener, a best friend and a fun loving spirit. I really can’t say enough good things about this girl. Best of all, she loves the outdoors, whether its rolling around in the grass or just people watching in the park, Coconut could spend her entire day outside.

﻿Coconut is approximately 1y 1m 1d old and is fully grown at 70 pounds. They are microchipped and up to date on all age-appropriate medical care. Their breed is unknown as we have not had a DNA test done.

dogs.name: And Peggy
dogs.description:
Meet And Peggy, the third Schuyler sister, who blended into the background during her two months at NYC ACC, but in her foster home has turned into a total scene-stealer in the best way. She’s fully housetrained and crate trained, and while she’s a strong girl, she walks nicely on her harness. She loves to play fetch (and monkey in the middle, if you have two willing humans!), and has discovered the joys of the flirt pole, but she balances her energy out with an equal number of hours of couch snuggles. She's tried to play with the resident dogs in the home, but they're all old and stodgy and have declined (which she accepts without putting up a fuss). 

Indoors, she’s a top-tier couch snuggler and a gentle giver of kisses to both humans and dogs. She’s food-motivated enough to train well without being overly intense about it. New environments or loud noises may startle her for a moment, but she recovers quickly and looks to her people for guidance.

See more of (And) Peggy on her foster mom's IG highlight reel @house_of_tan_gang (where she fits RIGHT in!)

dogs.general_personality: She is super friendly and loves getting belly rubs. She is super curious and loves to smell around.
dogs.daily_routine: When Calua wakes up at around 7 she takes a drink of water and then is taken for a potty break. She will then settle for her morning nap.  She is fed breakfast in the morning but eats whenever she would like (usually doesn't eat her breakfast until late afternoon). She naps most of the day and just follows us around, but as soon as she wakes up from her naps she usually gets some water and then walks towards the door to let us know she needs to go out. She gets dinner late at night since she doesn't eat her breakfast until later. She gets her night walk around 9 pm and then settles for bed around 11.
dogs.leash_behaviors: Very great on leash. She loves to sniff around so she pulls lightly occasionally but responds well to a small tug. She will follow you wherever you go.
dogs.crate_rating_when_alone: 2 - Appears to be taking well to crate training (may bark/cry initially when left alone but does settle within an hour)
dogs.crate_rating_detail: We have been working on positive reinforcement of the crate and she has made a lot of progress being left alone. She still barks and whines for about 20-30 minutes before settling.
dogs.other_quirks: She is a funny girl and loves to zoom around sometimes but is also just as happy sleeping.
dogs.what_makes_him_her_happy: She absolutely loves belly rubs and just being around you. She gets very excited for walks and will jump up and down. She also loves her bed and will launch herself into it.
dogs.what_makes_him_her_nervous: She isn’t a huge fan of other dogs on the street or quick movements around her butt.
dogs.other_displayed_behaviors: n/a
dogs.acclimated_to_environment: She has done super well, explored the house with no signs of fear, and seems to be unbothered by the city noises.

dogs.name: Ellie
dogs.description:
Ellie is an adorable walking oxymoron! Indoors, she is a couch potato who gives her belly to everyone, showing trust and her cuddly tendencies. Outside, she is an energetic ball of energy, wanting to get everywhere as fast as possible. People are not convinced when I tell them she is not a puppy. Ellie loves everyone she meets, and we are working on her excitement level about the many potential dog besties on every block. Pretty convinced this is the first time in her eight years that she has gone places on a leash, but she’s picking it up quickly. I suspect she would make an excellent hiking partner, considering how much she has turned the city into her personal parkour course. The girl can jump!

﻿Ellie is approximately 8y 3m 3d old and is fully grown at 37 pounds. They are microchipped and up to date on all age-appropriate medical care. Their breed is unknown as we have not had a DNA test done.

dogs.general_personality: Ellie is social and outgoing, but learning to control her excitement level will take a little while, since moving to the city is such a huge change. She can get overstimulated and escalate quickly, but not at all out of aggression, so we are working on strategies to help her approach each situation a little slower. At home, it is a polar opposite, as she has decided a specific spot on my couch is the best and prefers to stay there most of the time, napping, or waiting for someone to sit next to her and scratch her belly.
dogs.daily_routine: Ellie is an early riser, redecorating her crate as early as 5 AM. Between 6 and 6:30, she will give some light barking to let me know she wants to come out. She immediately takes her favorite spot on the couch while I make coffee and prepare breakfast for the dogs. We eat breakfast at 7 AM, and then go for a long morning walk. She returns to her post on the couch, occasionally playing with chew toys that I put near her, but mostly organizes the blanket and pillows to make a perfect spot to nap. Sometimes Ellie is somewhat of a Velcro dog, moving from room to room wherever I am, basically changing nap locations. We spend a little time working on training exercises, but only as long as she wants the treats involved. Around 2 PM, we go for a long afternoon walk. We find wide sidewalks that are still relatively busy with people and dogs so she can practice containing her energy. Like my resident dog, she sees every open door as an invitation, and freely introduces herself to everyone.  At 5 PM, the dogs have dinner, and Ellie is very good about eating near my dog, keeping to her own bowl. No signs of food guarding whatsoever. For the rest of the evening, she wants to cuddle. She will tap you with her paw to indicate she wants pets, and will keep doing this every time you stop. At any point if I need to step out, she will easily go into the crate, but her redecorating starts a lot earlier when it’s not overnight sleep time. Last walk is around 10 PM. By 11 PM, Ellie will go into her crate to go to sleep, and will rest until she wakes up at the crack of dawn to rejoin us.
dogs.leash_behaviors: Within minutes of meeting her, I realized she is the perfect candidate for a transitional leash, given how much she was pulling, wanting to sprint down the sidewalk. Since using the transitional leash, she is learning to walk on a leash really well. She takes cues to move to the side, and pulls much less. Ellie is not a fan of having part of the leash over her nose, but tries to slide it off less and less.
dogs.crate_rating_when_alone: 2 - Appears to be taking well to crate training (may bark/cry initially when left alone but does settle within an hour)
dogs.crate_rating_detail: The first night, she barked for 10 or 15 minutes before settling. The second night, she settled right away. Both mornings, though she was making it very clear that she was ready to come out of the crate, both at about 6 AM.
dogs.other_quirks: Ellie does not like getting a bath at all. She will collapse in a corner, avoiding it, and during the bath, insist that she keeps her face against you.
dogs.what_makes_him_her_happy: I’ve never seen a dog who rolls over so easily and often for belly rubs, but Ellie absolutely loves them. Has even fallen off the couch while trying to give as much belly as possible. She also loves going for walks, and does a happy prance while we get ready to walk out the door.
dogs.what_makes_him_her_nervous: Ellie can get overstimulated quickly when surrounded by a lot of excited people, or when she sees other dogs on the sidewalk. She is learning though.
dogs.other_displayed_behaviors: Only the overstimulation outside the home, but she just arrived in the city, and may soon be as relaxed as she is at home.
dogs.acclimated_to_environment: Within an hour of arriving at my place, she was giving her belly, showing trust, to both me and my resident dog. Ellie seems comfortable everywhere, as long as you keep chaos and excitement somewhat controlled. She’s not much of a barker, and has not shown interest in toys yet, but my resident dog is helping her learn how to dog.
dogs.currently_eating: I started Ellie immediately on my resident dog’s food, which is Natural Balance Limited Ingredient, Vegetarian formula, and she really enjoys it. She gets about 2 cups a day, split between two meals. Ellie is less interested in pumpkin toppers, but has eaten some of it. For treats, she loves the dehydrated sweet potatoes, the Halo blueberry dog biscuits, and Whimsies (like a vegan Greenie).

dogs.name: Shaun
dogs.description:
Shaun is an exceptionally kind-hearted, loyal, and gentle soul. He’s one of those dogs who brings an instant sense of calm just by being in the room. Shaun loves curling up next to his people for quiet cuddles and naps, and he’s happiest when he can simply be near his humans on a soft bed or cozy blanket. He enjoys easy walks, lounging around the house, and being part of a predictable daily routine. He’s very smart, eager to please, and generally well-behaved. Shaun is on the quieter side and can be a bit shy when meeting new people, but once he feels safe, his sweet and affectionate personality really comes out. Shaun is also a sensitive dog: he really does not like yelling, harsh voices, or very loud, chaotic environments. He can be slightly protective of “his” people and space. Shaun bonds deeply with his people. Whoever welcomes Shaun into their life will gain a devoted, sensitive family member and a whole lot of quiet warmth and love.

﻿Shaun is approximately 4y 0m 21d old and is fully grown at 36 pounds. They are microchipped and up to date on all age-appropriate medical care. Their breed is unknown as we have not had a DNA test done.

Although our dogs are listed as unknown breed, buildings with specific dog restrictions typically enforce their rules based on what breeds a dog appears to resemble. It's always important to keep that in mind and know your building's policies before adopting a dog.

dogs.general_personality: Shaun is shy, calm, and people-oriented. He’s soft-spoken and polite when meeting new people, more “quietly affectionate” than outgoing. Once he feels comfortable, his warm, cuddly personality shines through. He’s steady, sweet, loyal, and incredibly easygoing, making him a wonderful companion in almost any environment.

7am - walk to pee and poop
7:30am - 1 cup of dog food with 1 tbsp yogurt mixed in (we found this was kind of the only thing that got him to eat)
11am - walk to pee
3pm - walk to pee
5:30pm - 1 up of dog food with 1 tbsp yogurt mixed in 
7pm - walk to pee and poop
11pm - walk to pee
dogs.leash_behaviors: Walks very quickly, so pulls a little, but is generally really good and is completely non-reactive and responds to commands outside.
dogs.crate_rating_when_alone: 2 - Appears to be taking well to crate training (may bark/cry initially when left alone but does settle within an hour)
dogs.crate_rating_detail: He cries and barks a bunch when we leave and it takes him a while to settle down. He does not exhibit any other behaviors besides whining/crying and pawing at the crate. It seems like he does eventually settle but sometimes starts to cry or bark again if he hears something.
dogs.other_quirks: Nope
dogs.what_makes_him_her_happy: Spending time with us, cuddles, being on the couch or bed, snacks
dogs.what_makes_him_her_nervous: Being left alone, yelling, taking his things away
dogs.other_displayed_behaviors: Anxiety when left alone, guarding of his people
dogs.acclimated_to_environment: Shaun has acclimated extremely well to his new environment. He has had zero accidents and uses the bathroom only outside. He doesn’t chew, steal, or get into anything he shouldn’t. He has become protective of his stuff and people and has recently not reacted well to having things taken away. He’s calm and relaxed in our apartment, great when we bring him around friends, and completely unfazed by city noises, traffic, or commotion. He only reacts poorly to yelling and becomes extremely sad and goes far away. He adjusts smoothly to every new situation and has shown himself to be an easy, well-mannered, and remarkably adaptable dog.
dogs.currently_eating: Canidae all life stages dry food and plain yogurt

dogs.name: Pepper
dogs.description:
Hi! My name is Pepper. I'm having the best time adjusting to life in NYC. Loud noises - like a siren sometimes scare me, but I'm really good with the vacuum and when music is being played. I like to boop their ankles with my nose and to circle around them to keep them in one place. I go for walks in my bag all the time and have been on the subway and in a taxi. Though I haven't met any other dogs, I love to play my foster brother. I love the ball and all my squeaky toys. I love to nap - I'm a really good sleeper. I'm also growing so fast! I'm really smart and already know how to sit, lay down and go to "place" which is my bed. I don't cry in the crate unless I'm left for a long time - like over three hours - but I sleep in it at night and will sleep for a solid 6 hours. When I have to go to the bathroom, I use the pad and will cry from the crate. When I'm out of the crate, I know to use the pad, but sometimes I still have accidents. I don't love baths, but I tolerate them and I love to give kisses and snuggle on the couch.

﻿Pepper is approximately 0y 2m 5d old and may be 23 to 37 pounds when fully grown. They are microchipped and up to date on all age-appropriate medical care. Their breed is unknown as we have not had a DNA test done.

dogs.general_personality: Pepper is a little shy at first, but opens up very quickly! She loves to play and give kisses.
dogs.daily_routine:
Pepper wakes up between 5-6 am to go to the bathroom on the pad. Then she goes back to bed until 9am. around 9:45 She drinks water, eats, poops and pees and then we go for a long walk in her bag. We have a little training time where we practice her tricks - she's currently learning "paw" and "leave it" and then we play and she plays with her toys where she likes to play fetch with a ball. We also do a lot of mental stimulation where we hide treats for her to find in a towel. She's really smart so she needs a lot of mental training to tire out.

She eats lunch around 1 and then we go for another walk. She'll nap in her crate when I go for walk and then we come out, eat dinner and play some more around 6:45. We go for a last walk around 10:30 pm. She snuggles with us on the couch and then she gets into her crate for bed around 11:15 and she sleeps until 5 pm.
dogs.crate_rating_when_alone: 2 - Appears to be taking well to crate training (may bark/cry initially when left alone but does settle within an hour)
dogs.crate_rating_detail: She does great in the crate! She sleeps at night and only wakes up if she has to go to the bathroom, otherwise, we have to wake her up. If she's left alone for more than 3 hours, she sometimes cries.
dogs.other_quirks: She likes to boop your ankles and circle around your feet to try keep you in one place - like she's herding you.
dogs.what_makes_him_her_happy: Toys, treats, snuggles, giving kisses and walks in her bag.
dogs.what_makes_him_her_nervous: Baths, sirens, a dog barking in the hallway.
dogs.other_displayed_behaviors: No
dogs.acclimated_to_environment: Pepper is doing great! She loves going for walks

dogs.name: Hammie
dogs.description:
Hi there! My name is Hammie. It’s hard to believe I’m brand new both to the city and to the world, being only 2 months old, because I am such a good puppy! I also LOVE listening to the TV, so I’d be thrilled to listen to your favorite show with you. 

I love other dogs, and playing with my foster sister dog is my favorite way to spend my time. I want to spend time with my foster family’s cats; unfortunately, I think they’re a puppy like me and want to play with them, and they’re not so much a fan of that. 

My favorite toy is anything I can play tug of war with, but honestly, I love most anything I can fit in my mouth. Some of my toys are even cat toys because I’m so small. I haven’t learned yet to spit out cardboard toys or fluff rather than eating it, so I’m better off with actual dog toys than DIY ones. 

I’m a pro at potty pad training, but I’m still working on my enforced naps. My foster parents let me play for about an hour before I go down for a two hour nap, but I like to wake up earlier at an hour or an hour and a half. I’m getting better at it every day! I have a snuggle puppy that plays a heartbeat for me that I like to cuddle with during my naptime; my foster parents give me some kind of fun toy to help keep me occupied if I wake up early. I don’t like sleeping in a quiet room because every noise seems so loud, but I LOVE to sleep to the TV. White noise is only okay, but I love hearing people talk, so TV is perfect. 

I also really love going for walks in my puppy sling! Being outside is awesome, and I have some of my best naps while my foster parents are having a coffee walk with me in a sling. I am happiest around my people, and being held or laying on my people is my favorite thing in the world other than playing with my foster sister. I don’t really like being left alone right now, but who would when they’re less than 5 pounds and only 2 months old? I’m just a baby!

I’m brand new to the city and still have lots of learning to do! I am working on the commands “sit” and “lay down.” I’m an indoor puppy, so I use pads exclusively for potty time. My tummy has been a little unsettled since arriving in the big city, so I’m only eating chicken, rice, and pumpkin right now, but I love food and can’t wait til my stomach lets me have more treat and food options. 

My foster parents tell me every day how cute and small I am, so I must be pretty special. Do I sound like the right fit for your family? Apply to adopt me today at Muddy Paws Rescue.

dogs.general_personality: Dud is extremely cute and silly. Once he's comfortable, he will want to give his belly and snuggle close! It seems that his favorite thing to do is be a couch potato... but he does get excitable outside and will bulldoze through the leaves, and show off his hops when he gets a burst of energy!
dogs.daily_routine: Dudley is let out of his crate (slowly and sleepily) when foster wakes up around 7:15. He'll go to the bathroom in fosters yard/ on deck. Loves getting pets, following foster around, and may play with a toy a little throughout the day, but mostly wants to snooze the day away. If foster goes to office he sleeps in crate for 5 hours. Working on training exercises to build confidence to leash walk outside. He eats dinner around 5 and goes potty outside, more playing, pets or snoozing, and goes into his crate around 11 for a full nights sleep.
dogs.leash_behaviors: Dudley is currently afraid of going out to the street on leash so is not going on walks. He has  gotten comfortable with fosters small Brooklyn yard to go potty. When he stayed in the suburbs briefly, he seemed more comfortable with walking. We're hopeful he'll continue working up his confidence!
dogs.crate_rating_when_alone: 3 - Appears to be crate trained
dogs.crate_rating_detail: May whine briefly but settles for hours
dogs.other_quirks: Only one ear lifts up when he's listening intently! When he lays down, he goes down giant head first. He does happy grumbles when kissing your face. He's not an athlete and struts around on his low rider legs as best he can :)
dogs.what_makes_him_her_happy:
Snacks (blueberries and raspberries, also tried: cottage cheese, turkey, frozen mango chunks... loved all of these)
Snuggles (preferably curled up next to his crew, with a blanket)
dogs.what_makes_him_her_nervous: Not experienced with leash or stairs, so these things are a little nerve-wracking. Otherwise he's a really happy guy!
dogs.other_displayed_behaviors: No
dogs.acclimated_to_environment: Dud seemed a little unsure when he first got here, but decompressed fairly quickly. Minimal handling helped with this! He mostly sleeps on the couch.
dogs.currently_eating: PPP Sensitive Skin and Stomach (just what foster has on hand)

dogs.name: Butternut
dogs.description:
Her name is Butternut but she's as sweet as Princess Buttercup (IYKYK!)  Butternut loves to go for walks & would love an active family, but she's just as happy curling up on the couch & burying her head into you when she comes inside while you rub her belly. She loves people and is always smiling with her tongue out! She's very curious when on walks and loves to sniff. If a door is open, she wants to go inside to check it out. She has mostly been ignoring other dogs but occasionally wants to say hello. I think she'd do well with another dog in the house or being an only dog (she IS a Princess after all). She really enjoys her treats and her toys. Butternut is the sweetest, most polite pup. She will sit and "ask" to come up on the couch before jumping up and politely sits in the elevator when going outside. She will make you laugh and give you lots of cuddles and makes everyone she meets smile!

﻿Butternut is approximately 5y 2m 6d old, approximately 66 pounds, and we estimate their optimal weight to be about 45 pounds. They are microchipped and up to date on all age-appropriate medical care. Their breed is unknown as we have not had a DNA test done.

Although our dogs are listed as unknown breed, buildings with specific dog restrictions typically enforce their rules based on what breeds a dog appears to resemble. It's always important to keep that in mind and know your building's policies before adopting a dog.

This dog is available for adoption through Muddy Paws Rescue. If you're interested in adopting, the first thing you should do is begin the registration process at www.muddypawsrescue.org. If you are already a registered adopter with Muddy Paws Rescue, please email us at adoptionmeetings@muddypawsrescue.org.

dogs.general_personality: Butternut gives a cute little whine when you're not giving her the attention she thinks she deserves. She loves walking outside & walks like she has a mission. She's super curious about everything around her but also loves to snuggle on the couch.
dogs.daily_routine: Butternut gets a walk around 8am (foster mom is a night owl so she gets a later walk), breakfast is around 9am. She then takes a nap or plays for a few hours while in the house. We go out for a longer walk from around 1pm-3pm. We come home and she takes another nap or we play with toys til dinner around 5 or 6pm. We go out for another walk a bit after dinner. She gets some treats later in the evening and we have our final walk some time after midnight. Whenever Butternut needs to go out, she goes to the door and we go out for another walk. She's a very good sleeper and when it's bedtime, goes to her bed.
dogs.leash_behaviors: Butternut has a mission when she's on a walk. She will walk very fast and occasionally pull a bit. We're working on it. She also likes to go from side to side when she sees something that interests her. Open doors mean she's invited in. But she's usually responsive to commands and we're working on her leash walking. She's using a martingale collar & I got her a shorter 4' leash for better handling.
dogs.crate_rating_when_alone: 1 - Appears to need significant work on crate training (exhibits extreme signs of stress for over an hour)
dogs.crate_rating_detail: Butternut does not like the crate. But she is not destructive nor does she have any issues outside the crate. I got permission to leave her outside the crate when I was out rather than forcing her. She had treats etc in the crate but had no interest. I had her on cameras in the house and she basically just slept on the couch or played with her toys. I did have her confined to the living room with a gate and she would whine a bit when the gate went up as she knew I was leaving. She had a large area but mainly stayed on the couch or on the floor in front of it. She has no issues remaining outside the crate when I'm not home.
dogs.other_quirks:
Butternut is so cute. If we are in the elevator alone, she will sniff around. When someone else is in the elevator, she moves to the side & sits down. 
She also likes looking in glass doors when on a walk. She's very curious about what's going on around her & inside those doors.
dogs.what_makes_him_her_happy: Seeing people makes her happy. Being close to you, having her tummy rubbed or her tush scratched gives her joy. She's basically always smiling when she's not sleeping! She loves zooming around playing fetch.
dogs.what_makes_him_her_nervous: Butternut can get startled by loud noises outside but I think it's just a normal startle, not that she's fearful. She initially whines a bit when she knows you're leaving but stops before you even get out the door.
dogs.other_displayed_behaviors: She pulls a bit on the leash and is strong so would need more training but no other concerning behaviors.
dogs.acclimated_to_environment: Butternut has been here for 3 days and she's basically taken over the apartment. She's made herself at home & is a great housemate! She loves walking and stops to watch what's going on when she's outside. She's very curious about the horses and sounds of the city.
dogs.currently_eating: Kismet Chicken and Barley. I added some Stella & Chewy Chicken mix ins that I crumbled on top and some chicken broth.

dogs.name: Harley
dogs.description:
Meet Harley — a sweet, cuddly, affectionate boy who loves being close to his person. He’ll lean into you for snuggles and quiet time and has so much love to give once he feels safe.

He’s a sensitive guy who can be unsure in new situations, so he’ll do best with someone patient and calm who can help him feel safe and supported. With reassurance and consistency, he becomes noticeably more relaxed, trusting, and connected.

If you’re someone who values a gentle, loyal companion and understands the power of patience, Harley will be the perfect match ❤️

﻿Harley is approximately 8y 3m 2d old and is fully grown at 18 pounds. They are microchipped and up to date on all age-appropriate medical care. Their breed is unknown as we have not had a DNA test done.

dogs.general_personality: He’s a loving, cuddly, and sensitive dog who can be shy and a bit nervous in unfamiliar situations. Once he feels safe, he’s very affectionate and enjoys close companionship. He does best with calm environments and patient people who help him feel safe.
dogs.daily_routine: He usually wakes up around 6am, and we go straight outside for a potty break. After that he has breakfast and relaxes. He’ll typically go for another walk around 12pm and then have dinner around 6pm before another potty break or short walk. His final walk is around 9pm, and then he settles into his crate between 9:30–10pm and sleeps through the night until morning. During the day, he spends a lot of time napping, relaxing, and playing with his toys.
dogs.leash_behaviors: He’s great on the leash and doesn’t pull at all — he walks calmly and stays close. He may give a small bark when he sees strangers approaching, and he’ll perk up a bit when another dog passes by, but usually doesn’t bark at them. Overall, he’s very easy and enjoyable to walk with.
dogs.crate_rating_when_alone: 2 - Appears to be taking well to crate training (may bark/cry initially when left alone but does settle within an hour)
dogs.crate_rating_detail: When crated and home alone, he cries and whines for about 30 minutes before calming down. Once he settles, he rests quietly.
dogs.other_quirks: He loves sleeping under the blanket — if you’re on the couch with one, he’ll happily nudge his way underneath to snuggle in close.
dogs.what_makes_him_her_happy: He’s happiest cuddling in next to you for naps, and he’s more than content being a total couch potato. He’s the perfect show-binging partner and just loves being close and cozy.
dogs.what_makes_him_her_nervous: He can get nervous with sudden movements or being grabbed unexpectedly, especially around his head or from above. Strangers can also make him a bit uneasy at first, so slow, calm introductions work best. He just needs a little time and gentleness to feel safe and comfortable.
dogs.other_displayed_behaviors: He can react when he’s startled by sudden movements or unexpected touching, especially around his head or neck area. He may also feel uncomfortable around new people at first and needs slow introductions. With gentle handling, calm movements, and a bit of patience, he settles and remains relaxed.
dogs.acclimated_to_environment: He’s been adjusting well, but it has taken patience and consistency with a schedule. He’s still a bit unsure with new people and unfamiliar sounds or movements, but with gentle reassurance he settles and becomes more relaxed. Each day he’s been getting a little more comfortable and confident.
